I spent 3 months going deep on Solidity security.
Reentrancy. Flash loans. MEV. Proxy exploits. Wrote about all of it.
But something kept bothering me the whole time.
All this secure code we write — who's actually going to execute it?
Not a human. Not anymore.
AI agents are already executing smart contracts, managing DeFi positions, and facilitating DAO operations with minimal human intervention. 
Right now. On mainnet.
And most Solidity developers have no idea how the plumbing works.
So I'm starting a new series. Agents on Chain. 30 days.
Here's what we're covering:
→ Why AI agents can't use regular wallets → ERC-4337, session keys, and how you give an agent a spending limit → LangChain + Solidity: building real on-chain agent actions → Chainlink Functions: smart contracts that call AI → How agents get exploited — prompt injection, access control failures, adversarial inputs
At the end, I'm building something real. An autonomous DeFi risk monitor that detects and acts — on-chain, with capped authority.
My Solidity series was about writing secure code.
This one is about what happens when that code runs itself.
